I worked around it by using the same Mongoose connection with MongoStore:
javascript
var store = new MongoStore({
  db: require('./db.js').connection.db
});
. Yes, we have the same and we use the standard Mongo connection string (http://docs.mongodb.org/manual/reference/connection-string/#connections-standard-connection-string-format), with and without replica sets.
Also, if you check https://github.com/kcbanner/connect-mongo/blob/master/lib/connect-mongo.js#L100 , you see that if you provide a "node-mongo-native" DB object, it does not open a new connection and simply uses the one provided.
